ce:section.ce:para:
Having these primary results, we turn to calibrate the pH values to the EEM data sets by applying multivariate calibration methods. The back-propagation artificial neural network (BPANN) [46], as a widely used nonlinear multivariate calibration method, was carried out on the entire augmented data matrix containing 27 data sets with pH values from 2.0 to 14.0 as calibration (training) set (Table 1
                     ). The performance of the model was evaluated using a leave-one-out cross validation method and the selection of the optimum number of PCs for input layer and the right number of hidden layers nodes were performed according to the minimum value of the root mean square error of cross validation (RMSECV). Accordingly, the five first PCs as input layer and four nodes in the hidden layer were selected as the optimum numbers of these parameters. The RMSECV of predicted pH values in the calibration set was 0.067 which was 0.85% of the mean of the pH values, a very low value that validated the model. The predicted results are listed in Table 1 and are plotted versus their actual values as unfilled circles in Fig. 6
                     a.
